Date:  0/0/1941
Source:  NZ Slang
Author:  BAKER
Vol / Page:  44
Edition:
Quote:  Fire in the fern for trouble or smouldering discontent. The  expression to spread like fire in the fern, used of a rumour and even of an epidemic, is useful as well as alliterative. Dealing with the Maori Wars in the Sydney Telegraph as recently as February, 1940, a writer says: `The fire in the fern has now gone out. Justice is being done to the Maori', which reveals that in Australia the phrase is linked with New Zealand.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1946
